May 14 2008 	the good the bad and the ugly	We stayed at the Hotel on Mount Charleston this past Mothers' Day Weekend, checked in on Saturday the 10th of May, out on Sunday the 11th. So, what did I think???? Where here is the good:1)The room rates are great. I work in the travel industry, so I see alot of hotels and have alot of travel experience to compare this hotel/motel with others. I booked the hotel via TRAVELWORM.COM, they had/have amazingly affordable rates at this property, and for a weekend at that! Much better than booking with the hotel directly. 2) the rooms are nice and clean and quaint. Nothing fancy schmancy. Just cute and cozy. We had a room on the third floor, which also gave us a balcony. BUT FOREWARNING: there are NO ELEVATORS. I personally don't give a hoot, I like walking up and down stairs (good exercise) and you should too; but for those who are elderly or handicap, you will want a room on the ground floor. Perhaps folks with small children would prefer a ground floor as well. My kids didn't mind. 3) comfy beds. Very comfy. I slept good. 4) the grounds are nice and tranquil and quiet. I enjoyed just walking around and having some peace and quiet (with the exception of my three year old who turned into the demon child most of the weekend!) ;-) 5) nice lobby. has a very rustic feel to it. So you can imagine you are actually in some sort of ski resort area. (sorry, being from NorCal, I can NEVER consider MT Charleston a top notch ski resort destination!! Or ski destination of any kind, but apparently, they DO have a ski area up there. Go figure.) The Bad:1) the so-called &quot;spa&quot;. I sure as heck didn't see one. There was no spa to be found. As far as I know, it was just a private room where a woman did massages and body wraps and stuff. When I think of spa, I think of hydrotherapy tubs, dry sauna, steam room, all marble peacefulness and tranquility. So it is misleading to say they have a &quot;spa&quot;. Re-wording of that might be nice. Needless to say, I didn't get to take advantage of any spa treatments, as there was/is only one woman running the show there if you should want a massage or body wrap or whatever. 2) This is just a Mount Charleston thing but word to the wise: there are NO STORES ON THAT MOUNTAIN. You are at the mercy of the few lodges/hotels up there should you need anything from a stick of gum, to water, to food. So either stock up ahead of time, or plan on shelling out extra cash for such items. 3) while our room WAS cute and clean, it did NOT have some of the things mentioned on their website, like plasma tv, refrigerator, or little fireplace. The Ugly:1) the service. As previously mentioned, the service here leaves alot to be desired. While the people were nice enough and friendly, there is this sort of strange, lackadaisical attitude that permeates throughout the property. From the gal at the front desk to the service in the restuarant. This is NOT Hawaii folks, where you expect a more &quot;hang loose&quot; attitude. Needless to say, the service left alot to be desired. And it wasn't just this hotel. We went to eat at the Lodge on Mt Charleston and had the WORST service there. (like the waiter serving everybody BUT myself, then completely forgetting my breakfast...happy effin' mothers day, eh? My mate had to finally call him over and say um...where is my lady's meal?? Again, this was not at the hotel on MT Charleston, but further up the road at the LODGE) So perhaps this malaise or high altitude affects these folks on the hill, thus negating any sort of decent service. I don't know. But if they want to continue to have guests, everybody needs to step things up a notch or ten. 2) This being somewhat service related, once I realized OUR faux pas in not stocking up on drinks and snacks for the kids, I asked the lady at the front desk if there were any sort of stores, sundries, anything in the hotel or nearby. She said no, but they DO have a bistro that not only serves gourmet coffee but also you can get things like juice, chips, etc, ad nauseum. She mentioned they would be open in the morning at 7am. (we arrived around 5pm and the bistro was closed.) So, the next morning, we got up, and all I wanted was a good cup of joe and maybe a muffin, as well as some juice for the kids. We go downstairs, and the bistro was closed. We asked a gal at the front desk why it wasn't open, to which she replied, &quot;oh gee, I don't know, he should be here by now. But our restuarant opens at 8am!&quot; Now after an okay dinner the night before, I really didn't feel like sitting down at the same restaurant for breakfast. And it being mothers day, they were charging a much steeper fee for a meal and I don't think they were going to be selling just coffee. It was at this time we made the (bad) decision to drive further up the hill to the Lodge and get breakfast instead. Meanwhile, as we are departing the hotel, we see a young gent walking up and looks like he works at the Bistro. We ask him, &quot;hey! do you work at the bistro.&quot; To which he replied,&quot; yes, I do, however I am not working there today, I am working in the restuarant&quot; um. Ok. That is just....weird. I am sure there were many others who just wanted to grab something quick, and not have a big sit down overpriced breakfast, but whatever. We smelled a bit of a &quot;scam&quot; if you will, hence the reason we drove up to the Lodge (where we had the additional crap service and lackluster breakfast...once I was actually SERVED my breakfast). Seriously, I didn't really NEED a big breakfast, just some good coffee. (a treat for me, since I never drink it except on special occasions or once in a blue moon) It just seemed so petty and annoying to me. Why NOT open up the bistro?? They probably would have made MORE money off the folks with the same intent as us, than they did on their overpriced breakfast. So, that is my rant on the hotel. I think it has infinite potential. I think they need to have some big money come in, add an amazing, REAL spa in there, update a few things on the premises, and then do something about the help/service at the property. It can turn into an amazing little quaint getaway, especially for those of us who live in southern nevada. (p.s. do NOT eat the Southwest Salad at the restuarant. I LOVE super spicy food, but they go overboard with the spicy dressing. It had no taste was just...spicy. Viva Heartburn!)	
