Jul 23 2004	Older property struggling to keep repeat guests	My boyfriend took me to the hotel for a romantic getaway two weekends ago. The hotel is definitely old, but we were willing to overlook this to enjoy a night away in this historic property. There were at least two weddings happening when we arrived on Saturday and as a previous comment noted, the lobby was overtaken with guests and the dining room was being used as a banquet area. This meant that we had to have dinner in the bar, which turned out to be very nice. Our server was polite and efficient (as well as the hostess) and the cozy environment (with live music) just added to the very tasty food.Like any new guest in a room, we looked around after check-in and found no ice machines (ask at the bar or restaurant), mold in the grout of the bathroom, a very old smoky smell to the whole room (and even stronger in the mattress) and a dried liquid on the toilet seat (right under the special seat cover that said it was specially cleaned for us). A serious hazard that we viewed was the cleaning woman smoking while &quot;cleaning&quot; the rooms. She left the burning cigarette unattended on her cart, while in the rooms. We have also written to advise the Manager.Breakfast was enjoyed in the Dining Room, but the room seemed understaffed. Our server was very good, but rushed. The food was very nice, once again.We checked out and enjoyed a hike to Mary Jane Falls, which we recommend....if you have 3 hours to kill....since we weren't in as good a shape as we thought! Visiting in snow might be worth the trip to the hotel.	
Mar 4 2004	Never Again!	Booked a room on Tuesday for my adult daughter and myself for the Fri &amp; Sat of the same week. Friday was okay, although the room was disappointing. Small, old TV with no remote and few channels, bathroom grout black with mildew (inexcusable with all the wonderful cleaning products out there!) But Saturday was awful, to the extent that we ended up checking out at 4:30 pm after a very unsatisfactory discussion with the &quot;manager.&quot; We had booked the room for the rustic, ski-country ambiance, which included a huge wood-beamed lobby with a roaring fire to sit near after walks in the snow. What we found Sat. morning was a whole white lattice walled wedding chapel built INSIDE the hotel lobby. It completely blocked all view and access to the fireplace. As the day wore on, we discovered that there were EIGHT weddings scheduled back to back. We felt virtually trapped in our room between outings in the snow. They kept blocking off the main staircase up to our second floor room, so that the brides could make their grand entrances. The lobby was unavailable for relaxation, the bar didn't open until after noon, all the slot machines and the game arcade were shut down for the whole day and everytime we walked through the lobby someone would &quot;shush&quot; us because a(nother) wedding was in progress. At 4:00 pm with no sign of it abating, we expressed our dissatisfaction to the acting manager, Shane, who was rude and who basically told us our only option was to check out with no refund if we didn't like the situation. He tried to pass off all the lobby weddings as being due to &quot;an act of God.&quot; Imagine! At 7000+ feet in February, there might be snow to prevent garden weddings! We felt they could have warned us of the situation since we only booked three days ahead of time. We did end up leaving and what was supposed to be a relaxing weekend in the snowy mountains ended on a very sour note. They refused to refund even a part of the second night's room cost, even though we didn't stay. We will NEVER go back again.	
